Q : what are the methods which are present in optional class ? 
Ans : 
⭐1. of(value) - Creates Optional only if value is NOT null.

⭐ 2. ofNullable(value) - Creates Optional with null OR non-null value.

⭐ 3. empty() - Returns an empty Optional.

⭐ 4. isPresent() - Returns true if value is present.

⭐ 5. isEmpty() - Returns true if value is NOT present.

⭐ 6. get() - Returns value inside Optional.
❌ Throws exception if value is missing → not recommended.

⭐ 7. orElse(defaultValue) - Returns value if present, else returns defaultValue.

⭐ 8. orElseGet(Supplier) - Similar to orElse, but default value is created only if required.

⭐ 9. orElseThrow() - Throws exception if value is missing.

⭐ 10. ifPresent(Consumer) - Runs logic only if value is present.

⭐ 11. ifPresentOrElse(Consumer, Runnable) - Runs logic when value is present OR alternate logic when value missing.

⭐ 12. map(Function) - Transforms the value inside Optional.

⭐ 13. flatMap(Function) - Same as map, but for nested Optional values.

⭐ 14. filter(Predicate) - Returns value only if it matches a condition.


  	4 . default keyword : 
	default keyword is used in interface to make incomplete method complete. it is always used with 
    non static method.

	Default Method

	1: Declared using the keyword default inside an interface.

	2: It has a body (implementation) inside the interface.

	3: “We use the default keyword in an interface to put common logic that can be shared across all implementing classes.
        This way, we don’t need to write the same implementation again and again in every class — they can directly use 
		the default method from the interface if they want. And if a class wants a different behavior, it can simply 
		override that default method.”
		Yes — the main purpose of default methods is to avoid unnecessary duplicate implementation in multiple classes by
		keeping common logic in the interface itself.
	
	
	overrding the method in class: so if we want we can change the logic 
	
    interface Vehicle {
    default void start() {
        System.out.println("Vehicle is starting...");
    }
	}

	class Car implements Vehicle {
		@Override
		public void start() {
			System.out.println("Car is starting...");
			Vehicle.super.start(); // calling Vehicle interface's default method
		}
	}

	public class Main {
		public static void main(String[] args) {
			Car car = new Car();
			car.start();  // calls Car's start() and then Vehicle's default start()
		}
	}
	
	
	without overrding the method in class:
	
	interface Vehicle {
    default void start() {
        System.out.println("Vehicle is starting...");
    }
	}

	class Car implements Vehicle {
		// ❌ No override — Car will use Vehicle's default start() method
	}

	public class Main {
		public static void main(String[] args) {
			Car car = new Car();
			car.start();  // directly calls Vehicle's default method
		}
	}

	
	
	

    5. Static keyword  : 
	static keyword is used to make complete static method inside interface .it keeps the 
	implementation inside interface which we dont want to share amoung other class.  
	
	Static Method

	1: Declared using the keyword static inside an interface.

	2: It also has a body, but — it belongs to the interface itself, not to the implementing classes.

	3: So, you cannot override a static method in the implementing class.

	4: It is called using the interface name, not the class or object.
	
	interface Vehicle {
    static void repair() {
        System.out.println("Vehicle is being repaired...");
		}
	}

	class Car implements Vehicle {
		// Can't override repair()
	}

	public class Main {
		public static void main(String[] args) {
			Vehicle.repair(); // ✅ correct
			// new Car().repair(); ❌ not allowed
		}
	}

	
	
