Q4 :  boxed() method in strema api ?
Yes — we use boxed() to convert primitive values into their object (wrapper) types.

So when you write:

IntStream intStream = IntStream.of(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);
Stream<Integer> stream = intStream.boxed();	

“We use boxed() to convert primitive stream elements like int into their wrapper objects like Integer, 
so that we can use object-based Stream operations such as collect().

coding ex : 


import java.util.List;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;
import java.util.stream.IntStream;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        List<Integer> list = IntStream.of(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
                                      .boxed()
                                      .collect(Collectors.toList());

        System.out.println(list);
    }
}


Output:
[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

Explanation:

IntStream.of(1,2,3,4,5) → creates primitive int stream.
boxed() → converts primitive int into Integer objects(Wrapper object means Integer).
collect(Collectors.toList()) → converts stream into List<Integer>.


